ProtoDeclare.@appinfo:
The HAnimBehavior node models a single humanoid behavior either for an
entire body or simply parts of a body. It collects a TimeSensor clock with a single
PositionInterpolator and multiple OrientationInterpolator nodes to provide a single
humanoid behavior.

-children.#comment:
shared common input for single TimeSensor animating all interpolators,
since different Behaviors may have different cycleInterval durations
TODO: add other X3D 3.0 TimeSensor fields (pause etc.)
Not supported: animated translation of individual joints
pass in key/keyValue array pairs for single PositionInterpolator

pass in key/keyValue array pairs and expose named output for each OrientationInterpolator,
joint by joint

field.@appinfo:
Supported Level of Articulation (LOA) support needed by authored HAnimBehavior
set of OrientationInterpolator values. Legal values 0 1 2 3.
is this behavior enabled?
how long do these interpolators take to execute?

whether or not this behavior loops (e.g. walking) or is single shot (e.g.
shake hands).

when time now >= startTime isActive becomes true and TimeSensor becomes
active

when stopTime becomes <= time now isActive becomes false and TimeSensor
becomes inactive

when time now >= pauseTime isPaused becomes true and TimeSensor becomes
paused

when resumeTime becomes <= time now isPaused becomes false and TimeSensor
becomes inactive

cycleTime sends a time outputOnly at startTime and also at the beginning
of each new cycle
isActive true/false events are sent when TimeSensor starts/stops running
isPaused true/false events are sent when TimeSensor is paused/resumed

current elapsed time since TimeSensor activated/running cumulative in
seconds and not counting any paused time
continuously sends the absolute time (since January 1 1970)

fraction_changed continuously sends value in range [0 1] showing time
progress in the current cycle.

-children.#comment:
design alternative: move TimeSensor out of the prototype, instead expose
set_fraction globally to all interpolators

note that other nodes following the first node in the ProtoBody are not
rendered but remain active nevertheless

ProtoDeclare.@appinfo:
The HAnimBodyBehaviorChooser node allows an author to select one of several
HAnimHumanoid bodies and simultaneously apply multiple HAnimBehavior animations to
the active body. Individual behaviors may be enabled or disabled at any time.
